We recommended that Management:

 Direct the City Accountant and CGSO to retrieve the records/reports and source documents that would establish details of the irreconcilable items in the SL and RPCPPE and determine the adjustments that would be recorded in the books;

Instruct the City Accountant to record in the books the land which was included in the RPCPPE amounting to ₱2.18 million. Likewise, instruct the Inventory Team and the CGSO to update the RPCPPE and records, respectively, for the Land recorded in the books amounting to ₱8.58 million;

Determine the fair market values of the 10 lots with a total area of 42,628.75 square meters which were included in the submitted RPCPPE but not recorded in the books and the five lots with a total area of 90,644.00 square meters included in the CTO inventory of land owned by the LGU and with title in the of the City as basis for recording in the books of accounts;

Instruct the City Assessor to investigate and determine the proof of ownership of the LGU on the 120 lots with total area 799,237.00 square meters with tax declaration in their records in the name of the City. Thereafter, determine its fair market value to be used in recording in the books by the City Accountant and updating of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee and records of the CGSO.

Conduct a comprehensive inventory of all its real properties and ascertain which are covered with OCTs/TCTs;

For titled properties but the original copies of the OCTs/TCTs thereof could not be located, initiate the process to reconstitute the titles thereto;

For untitled properties, conduct cadastral surveys thereof and expedite the processing of the titles thereto in the name of the City; and

Instruct the City Accounting Office and the CGSO to maintain complete subsidiary records based on the inventory conducted and perform regular reconciliation of the balances thereof.

We recommended that the Management instruct the: 

City Engineer to provide the City Accountant with copy of the Certificate of Project Completion and Acceptance of the completed projects amounting to ₱29.2 million, to serve as basis by the City Accountant in recording completed projects as PPE;

City Engineer and City Accountant make a reconciliation of the completed and on-going projects annually as of year-end to ensure that completed projects are properly closed to the appropriate PPE account.  Any unpaid amount due to delay of the submission of billing by the contractor should be recognized as payable;

City Accountant to provide the periodic depreciation charges for these completed projects to allow fair presentation of the affected accounts in the year-end financial statements; 

City Engineer assign Project Number for all projects to be implemented by the City for easy identification, monitoring and recording the same;

City Accountant make the necessary correcting entries to revert the cost of Construction of City Hall- Phase I and accumulated depreciation recorded; and

City Accountant to transfer the CY 2020 year-end CIP balances, from the one SL card maintained for CIPs by the CAO to the required CIPLC, reconstructing the CIP balances per specific type of the asset constructed per Chart of Accounts.  Henceforth, to maintain the appropriate CIPLC, for each specific type of the asset constructed, whether thru straight contract or by administration.  Also, to ensure that all the required data in the CIPLC are properly indicated therein and upon completion of the project, reclassify the total CIP cost to the proper asset account using the data in the CIPLC as reference.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;

The General Service Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components;

The City Engineer to provide the City Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The City Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and

The City Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:

Adopt prescribed control procedures in the receipt, inventory and issuance of donations- in kind, and record the proper cost of the ending inventory based on the value declared by the donor, if available, or using the prevailing market price of the donated items;

Require the concerned offices/units to properly categorize the Donations- in Kind received by the City and intended for COVID-19 response reported in the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for consolidation;

Require the CDRRMO to submit a consolidated report on Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances, separately for Cash and In-Kind transactions, to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnished the Auditor, as required in COA Circular No. 2014-009;

Require the Property/Supply Officer to maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM to properly account for the ending inventory balances; and

Require the City Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements information pertaining to DRRM not evident on the face of the financial statements.

We recommended that Management take the following immediate courses of action: 

Take appropriate action to resolve this recurring deficiency considering the significance of the affected account in the financial statements of the City;


Consider assigning additional personnel in the Accounting Office who will maintain the SLs pertaining to the Loans Receivable – Others account; 


Require the CAO to maintain SLs and prepare Aging Report that will aid Management in the monitoring and collection of the Loans Receivable.  Also, for the CAO to regularly reconcile the SL balances with the GL balances and update the recording/posting of transactions at all times;

Further, require the CAO to conduct reconciliation with the records of other concerned departments, and adjust the books, if necessary; and


The concerned offices to conduct a thorough evaluation of the existing Loans Receivable. Intensify collection efforts and institute legal remedies, if warranted.  Furthermore, strengthen internal controls in the granting, monitoring and collection of loan assistance to ensure the sustainability of the program.

We recommended that Management:

Designate specific personnel to work on the transfer of the title of the 203 lots in the name of the City and appropriate funds to cover the cost of transferring the titles;

Require the CAO to reconcile their records with the CTO;

Require the CAO to maintain an SL and RPLC for Land and reconcile the same with the GL control account periodically; and 

Require the Inventory Team to prepare a complete inventory report of PPEs, including the real properties, and have it reconciled with the GSO records. Thereafter, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the report

We recommended that Management require the:

City Accountant to conduct a thorough analysis of the CIP account in coordination with the City Engineer.  Completed projects should be closed to the appropriate PPE account.  Any unpaid amount should be recognized as Payable account, if it is still feasible under the existing rules and regulations;

City Engineer to provide the City Accountant with copy of the Certificate of Project Completion and Acceptance of these completed projects, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor, to serve as basis by the City Accountant in recording completed projects as PPE;

City Accountant to provide periodic depreciation charges for these completed projects to allow fair presentation of the affected accounts in the year-end financial statements.

BAC to remind participating contractors in future biddings for infrastructure projects to comply with existing regulations, including requesting for final billing and putting up with the required warranty security on completed projects, to avoid occurrence of this irregular practice by some contractors.

We recommended that Management:

Require the CHRMO to formulate a Human Resource Plan and issue a uniform policy guidelines on the hiring of JO personnel to appropriately determine the necessity of the hiring thereof and as well as to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;

Reduce/limit hiring of JOs and instead fill up vacant plantilla positions in the LGU;

Evaluate and determine the appropriate personnel complement of each office/department in the City Government and effect the necessary amendments in their respective plantilla, if warranted.

