We recommended the following courses of actions, to address the deficiencies noted:

Management takes appropriate action to resolve this recurring deficiency considering the significance of the affected account in the financial statements of the City;

Management consider assigning additional personnel in the accounting who will maintain the subsidiary ledger pertaining to the Loans Receivable – Others account;

Accounting department maintains subsidiary ledgers and aging that will aid management in monitoring and collecting its loans receivable.  Regularly reconcile the balances with the GL balances and update recording/posting of transactions at all times;

Accounting department conduct reconciliation with the CCDO and CAO receivable records, if any, and adjust the books, if necessary.

Management to conduct a thorough evaluation of the existing loans receivable, intensify collection efforts and institute legal remedies, if warranted.  Furthermore, strengthen internal control system over the grant, monitoring and collection of loan assistance to ensure the sustainability of the program.

We recommended that the City Accountant: 

Effect the adjusting entries in the General Fund and Trust Fund Books to recognize the various equipment procured totaling ₱1,538,834.93 detailed in Annex 8;

Book-up all the PPE acquired in prior years out of the Trust Fund that were not recognized in the books of accounts; 

Provide the corresponding depreciation for all unrecorded PPEs after recognizing/transferring them in the General Fund books following the recommended pro-forma entries; and

Maintain separate General Journal for the Trust Fund Proper.

